This utility functions as a smart routing resolver, checking if the `view` argument represents an include tuple or a standalone path. It handles string-based view names by resolving them into actual callable objects before constructing the appropriate URL pattern class.

```python
def url(regex, view, kwargs=None, name=None, prefix=''):
    """As url() in Django."""
    if isinstance(view, (list, tuple)):
        # For include(...) processing.
        urlconf_module, app_name, namespace = view
        return URLResolver(regex, urlconf_module, kwargs, app_name=app_name, namespace=namespace)
    else:
        if isinstance(view, six.string_types):
            if not view:
                raise ImproperlyConfigured('Empty URL pattern view name not permitted (for pattern %r)' % regex)
            if prefix:
                view = prefix + '.' + view
            view = get_callable(view)
        return CBVRegexURLPattern(regex, view, kwargs, name)
```

The function abstracts away configuration differences between simple view patterns and complex includes. Note that reliance on `get_callable` means your views must be correctly discoverable within your Python environment for this to work.
